   <h1>Final question: align bore?</h1>
   <b>mccomas(-at-)intercom.net</b><br/>
   <i>2004-09-25 23:57:19+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Hi Mark,
          I was working last week with a friend who is an independent mechanic 
for specializing in fine vintage German cars.  As a special favor to one of his 
customers, he is working on the bottom end of a vintage Pontiac.  The fit of 
the bearings is of particular importance -- so he is using the plastic gauge 
product to be certain the oil clearances are correct.  In case you are not 
familiar with this, it looks like fine spaghetti; you put an inch or so along 
the bearing face, parallel to the axis of the crankshaft; then you see how how 
it squishes down.  The manufacturer gives you a handy little ruler kind of 
thing.  I don't know if this product is applicable for non-split bearings, but 
you could certainly check the split bearings this way.  Years ago I remember 
seeing the techs using fine (soft) solder, which got mashed down to a couple of 
mils, when they measured it with a micrometer.  In all cases (it goes without 
saying) the bearing house must be torqued to spec.  If you take the 
measurements carefully, then you know firsthand.  Just bolting-up an engine 
does not sound like good practice to me; YMMV.  All the best... Glenn

========== REF =============
Date: Sat, 25 Sep 2004 11:04:57 -0700
To: Type 2 List 
From: Mark Hineline 

Anyway, I got a split decision on the align bore, AKA line bore. Some 
responses said I should do it, some said not to (given the assumptions 
under which I'm building), and one said don't do it because I may not 
be able to find bearings.

As for the oversized bearings, Boston Bob has assured me that whatever 
I need, he has; all I have to do is specify the grind of my crank.

So I'm down to I'd better do it, and it's okay if I don't do it.

Once more, the question is whether to have the aluminum case from a 
2.0L align bored. I would like to get maybe 30,000-50,000 miles out of 
this engine. After that, I am going to pull out all the stops and have 
B. Bob build me an engine.</pre>


